  "prompt": "What does add on item on Amazon mean?",
  "response": "An \"Add-on Item\" on Amazon refers to a product that is only available for purchase in conjunction with other items in your shopping cart, typically because the item itself is low-cost or inexpensive. These items do not meet the minimum order amount required for free shipping, so Amazon encourages customers to add more items to their cart to reach that threshold.\n\nKey Characteristics of Add-on Items:\n\n1. **Low Price**: Add-on items are usually inexpensive, often priced under $10, though the exact threshold can vary.\n2. **Minimum Order Requirement**: To purchase an Add-on Item, your total order must meet a certain minimum amount, which is typically $25 for free shipping eligibility.\n3. **Not Sold Individually**: You cannot purchase an Add-on Item on its own; it must be part of a larger order.\n4. **Free Shipping**: If your total order meets the minimum amount, the Add-on Item will be included in your qualifying order and shipped for free.\n\n**Example Scenario**: If you find a pack of pencils marked as an Add-on Item for $5, you cannot purchase just one pack of pencils. Your total order must be at least $25 to include the pencils as part of your purchase.\n\nIn summary, Add-on Items are a way for Amazon to manage the cost of shipping low-value goods by requiring customers to make a larger purchase.",
